2024-02-20

Random Coefficients Model (Model 3) Visualized

Understanding what random effects are (and why we care about their variance) is among the hardest components of learning multilevel modeling. However, were now in a position to explore the data graphically to get a sense of what were analyzing

This vignette makes use of some great code by Rens van de Schoot

Random Coefficients model

In the slides, we review the random coefficients model which is (for this example) a two-level model, with a predictor at level 1 (center-SES or cses in our data set), and the outcome also at level 1 (mathach).

Unlike models 1 and 2, where our focus is on level 2 units (schools) here, were going to delve within each school and ask about the relationship between a students cses level and that students mathach score.

Visualizing the data

First, lets visualize the cses - mathach relationship without respect to school.

Heres an overall plot of all \(n = 7185\) students cses and math achievement scores. It looks pretty incoherent. Given the known hierarchical structure of the data, this is not surprising, so we should try to understand whats happening within each school and between schools.

However, we still see that, ignoring the clustering, theres some degree of linear relationship between a students SES and his or her math achievement score.

Lets sample 50 schools (there are 160 total) and visualize the differences. We do this because its hard to see whats going on across all 160.

First, lets just look at the scatterplot with schools identified as colors.

schools <- sample(HSB$school, 50)

Sampledata <- HSB[is.element(HSB$school,schools), ]


ggplot(data = Sampledata, aes(x = cses, y = mathach, col = school)) +
  geom_point(size = 1, alpha = .8, position = "jitter") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  scale_color_gradientn(colours = rainbow(50)) +
  labs(title    = "SES and Math Achievement",
       subtitle = "with different colors for students in different schools")

Ok that still looks a bit messy! But lets add a least-squares regression line for each school. This is an OLS regression line using only the data for that school.

ggplot(data = Sampledata, aes(x = cses, y = mathach, col = school, group = school)) +
  geom_point(size = 1, alpha = .7, position = "jitter") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  scale_color_gradientn(colours = rainbow(50)) +
  geom_smooth(method = lm,
              se     = FALSE,
              size   = .4, 
              alpha  = .7) + # to add regression line
  labs(title    = "SES and Math Achievement",
       subtitle = "The within-school regression lines")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

We can see that most of the lines have positive slope, but there are a few that do not!

Using Model 3, we will do two things:

  1. We will attempt to get overall average estimates these regression equations
  • \(\gamma_{00} =\) weighted average of \(\beta_{0j}\) the school-level regression intercepts
  • \(\gamma_{10} =\) the weighted average of \(\beta_{1j}\) the school-level slopes for the cses - mathach relationship
  1. The variability across schools in \(\beta_{0j}\) and \(\beta_{1j}\)
  • Since our equations for the gammas include a random effect of each school, we can obtain variability estimates by working with these random effects \(u_{0j}\) and \(u_{1j}\)

In model 3, were not attempting to explain why schools have different intercepts and slopes, so \(u_{0j}\) and \(u_{1j}\) for each school are simply the amount by which that school differs from the mean intercept (\(\gamma_{00}\)) and mean slope (\(\gamma_{01}\)), respectively. Theyre essentially level-2 error terms.

Fitting Model 3, the Random Coefficients 2-level model

From the slides, we know that our combined equation for the hierarchical model with cses as level-1 predictor, mathach as outcome, and both random intercepts (\(\beta_{0j}\)) and slopes (\(\beta_{1j}\)) is:

\[ Y_{ij} = \gamma_{00} + \gamma_{10}(cses) + u_{0j} + u_{1j}(cses) + r_{ij} \]

So that means, our mixed-effects output should contain estimates of 2 fixed effects:

  • \(\gamma_{00}\), the weighted average intercept across schools (scaled to be the grand mean)
  • \(\gamma_{10}\), the weighted average cses-mathach slope across schools

Note that we do not estimate \(\beta_{0j}\) or \(\beta_{1j}\) directly, but they can be computed. Generally, thats not our goal, but we could use these estimates for data in other analyses

We also should have estimates of the variances of 3 random effects

  • \(\text{Var}(u_{0j}) = \tau_{00}\)
  • \(\text{Var}(u_{1j}) = \tau_{11}\)
  • \(\text{Var}(r_{ij}) = \sigma^{2}\)

AND we have a new term, a covariance between \(u_{0j}\) and \(u_{1j}\)

  • \(\text{Cov}(u_{0j},u_{1j}) = \tau_{10}\)

Lets now estimate our mixed-effects parameters

model3 <- lmer(mathach ~ cses + (cses|school), data = HSB)

summary(model3)

Adding level 1 predictors with the random coefficients model

We can add as many level-1 predictors as we like. If we want to also model the level-1 slopes for these predictors as random, we need to change how our random-effects syntax looks. It is very similar to the combined equation though:

mod3a <- lmer(mathach ~ cses + sex + (cses + sex | school), data =HSB)

Model equation: \[ Y_{ij} = \gamma_{00} + \gamma_{10}(cses) + \gamma_{20}(sex) + u_{0j} + u_{1j}(cses) + u_{2j}(sex) + r_{ij} \]

Heres our results. Note the new rows in the Random Effects part of the output

Not only do we have a new variance (\(\text{Var}(u_{2j}) = \tau_{22}\)), we have two new covariances, in fact, we have a 3 by 3 variance-covariance matrix \(\textbf{T}\):

\[ \begin{bmatrix} \tau_{00} &. &. \\ \tau_{10} &\tau_{11} &. \\ \tau_{20} &\tau_{21} &\tau_{22} \end{bmatrix} \] The lower triangle (including the diagonal terms) are the only unique terms here. The diagonal lists the 3 random effect variances (of the random intercept, cses slope, and sex slopes in that order). The other entries are the covariances between those 3 terms. For example, \(\tau_{10}\) is the covariance between the random effect \(u_{0j}\) and \(u_{1j}\)

In the output from r, we only get this lower triangle including \(\tau_{10}\), \(\tau_{20}\), and \(\tau_{21}\). The variances are given in the variance column, along with \(\sigma^{2}\) which is the variance of the level-1 residuals (\(r_{ij}\))

##  Groups   Name        Std.Dev. Corr         
##  school   (Intercept) 2.82346               
##           cses        0.78492  -0.020       
##           sexMale     0.92911   0.004  0.406
##  Residual             6.02945

Here we can see that \(\tau_{10} = -0.02\), \(\tau_{20} = 0.004\), and \(\tau_{21} = 0.406\). This helps us understand how the varying terms relate within each school.

Finally, we can ask how much variance at level-1 weve reduced by adding sex as a level 1 predictor. We can use the CSES model as the comparison.

(36.700 - 36.3543) / 36.700
## [1] 0.009419619

So despite the average slope for sex being significantly different from zero, we havent explained much more variance by adding it.

Finally, we can get confidence intervals for all parameters. Remember, the confidence intervals for the variances are now for standard deviations. This is due to stability issues behind the scenes in the lmer package. Also, it will often take a while to compute these when there are more parameters. So here we have a number of variance parameters. Well learn different inference procedures over the next 2 weeks.

mod3b <- lmer(mathach ~ cses + sex + minority + (cses | school), data =HSB)
